\description{
The Small Molecule (SML) table is mandatory in the mzTab-M format and
provides abundances along with annotations on the small molecules of an
analysis result. All columns in this table need to be tab-delimited and no
empty cells are allowed (\code{"null"} must be used for missing values, for
columns that support that).

Each row of the small molecule section is intended to report one final result
to be communicated in terms of a molecule that has been quantified. In many
cases, this may be the molecule of biological interest. In general, different
adduct forms for the same molecule would be reported in the \emph{Small Molecule
Feature} (SMF) section.

A detailed description of the SML format and its columns is provided in the
\href{https://github.com/HUPO-PSI/mzTab-M/blob/main/specification_documents/mzTab_format_specification_2_1-M.adoc#63-small-molecule-section}{respective section}
of the mzTab-M specification.

The functions to create and format the SML content are:
\itemize{
\item \code{sml_create()}: main function that creates the SML table based on the
provided abundance matrix and small molecule annotation information.

The function automatically:
\itemize{
\item Formats the abundance matrix \code{x} (renaming column names to
\code{"abundance_assay[n]"})
\item Adds the required \code{"SML_ID"} column with a running integer representing
the primary key (unique ID) for each molecule.
\item Populates missing mandatory columns with \code{"null"} strings.
\item Sets the line prefix column.
\item Orders the columns according to the mzTab-M specification.
}

After \code{sml_create()}, required study variable abundance columns should
be either added manually or using the \code{sml_add_study_variable_columns()}
function. These required columns contain the average and variation
of molecule abundances across samples for a particular study variable.
\item \code{sml_add_study_variable_columns()}: \emph{completes} the SML table created
with \code{sml_create()} by adding columns with aggregated assay values
(molecule abundances) per study variable(s). Study variables have to be
listed in the MTD section provided with the \code{mtd} parameter (e.g.
\code{"study_variable[1]"}) where also the aggregation functions must be
defined (e.g. \code{"study_variable[1]-average_function"}). This aggregation
and variation functions has to be defined using the respective MS CV
ontology term (e.g. \code{"MS:1002962"} for the mean and \code{"MS:1002963"} for
the coefficient of variation). See \link{MTD-export} for details on the MTD
section.

The function:
\itemize{
\item gets all study variables from the metadata section (\code{mtd})
\itemize{
\item for each study variable:
\item gets the assay references from MTD
\item gets the summary functions (for average and variation) from MTD
(resolving the MS CV term to the respective R function)
\item gets the referred abundance columns in \code{x}
\item calculates the summary statistic and these as additional columns to
\code{x}.
}
}
\item \code{sml_sort()}: sorts the columns of an SML table into the expected order.
}
}
\details{
All parameters passed to the \code{sml_create()} function must be \strong{fully named}.
}
